t from `role`, `content_text`, `tool_name`,\n    33\t   `event_kind`, and redacted `source_record`\n    34\t\n    35\tThat means the transcript list must be readable without knowing the original\n    36\tmachine's file paths, working-directory state, branch state, or raw provider\n    37\tsession id.\n    38\t\n    39\t## 2. Sharing Session Details\n    40\t\n    41\tA developer uses an agent to produce a change and opens a pull re\n[TRUNCATED]\n  55\tfor example whether a payments edge case was considered.\n    56\t\n    57\tThe POC only captures redacted session records. It does not create web links,\n    58\tpublish metadata, or attach sessions to pull requests.\n    59\t\n    60\tExpected access pattern:\n    61\t\n    62\t1. start from a pull request, branch, change, or commit\n    63\t2. read its future `gitbutler:agent-sessions` relationship set\n    64\t3. resolve those session keys on the `project` target\n    65\t4. render each session's transcript timeline from the slim transcript records\n    66\t5. use redacted `source_record` for provenance and later normalization upgrades\n    67\t\n    68\tThat means branch/PR metadata should point to sessions, not contain copies of\n    69\tsession transcripts.\n    70\t\n    71\t## Many-to-Many Relationships\n    72\t\n    73\tSessions and code review objects are not one-to-one.\n    74\t\n    75\tOne branch or pull request may involve multiple sessions:\n   110\t\n   111\t- sessions that exist before code is written\n   112\t- one session associated with many branch or review objects\n   113\t- many sessions associated with one branch or review object\n   114\t- branch or commit associations being added after capture\n   115\t\n   116\t## POC Direction\n   117\t\n   118\tThe first POC should:\n   119\t\n   120\t- write redacted, shareable-ready `gitbutler:*` keys\n   121\t- keep session data on the `project` target by default\n   122\t- use a durable session key independent of branches and commits\n   123\t- keep 